    </div>

    <p>The critical question: does oral collagen actually reach your skin? For years, skeptics argued that collagen is broken down into amino acids during digestion, making oral supplementation useless. Modern research has settled this debate. Hydrolyzed collagen peptides (2-5 kilodaltons) are absorbed intact through the gut and circulate as di- and tri-peptides like prolyl-hydroxyproline. These peptides reach the dermis, where they act as <strong>signaling molecules</strong> that instruct fibroblasts to ramp up collagen, elastin, and hyaluronic acid synthesis. This is not about replacing skin collagen directly — it is about telling your skin cells to make more.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card"><strong>Hydrolyzed peptides absorb intact</strong><p>A 2012 study in the <em>Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry</em> used mass spectrometry to track collagen peptides in human blood after oral intake, confirming that bioactive di- and tri-peptides reach circulation.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><strong>Peptides signal fibroblasts</strong><p>Once in the dermis, collagen-derived peptides bind to fibroblast receptors and activate genes for collagen, elastin, and hyaluronic acid production — essentially "tricking" skin cells into building more structural protein.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><strong>Works for all skin types</strong><p>A 2019 meta-analysis in the <em>Journal of Drugs in Dermatology</em> pooled 11 studies and found consistent benefits across skin types, ages, and ethnicities. Photoaged and naturally aged skin both responded.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><strong>Measurable at 8-12 weeks</strong><p>Peer-reviewed trials consistently show meaningful wrinkle depth reduction, elasticity gains, and hydration improvements by week 8, with peak effects around week 12.</p></div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2021 systematic review in the <em>International Journal of Dermatology</em> analyzed <strong>19 randomized controlled trials with 1,125 participants</strong> and concluded that hydrolyzed collagen supplementation significantly improved skin hydration, elasticity, and wrinkle depth. The review called the evidence "robust and consistent" — a rare endorsement for a consumer supplement category.</p>
      <cite>International Journal of Dermatology, 2021 — 19-study meta-analysis</cite>
    </div>

    <h3>Collagen Type Matters: Type I vs II vs III for Skin</h3>

    <p>Not all collagen is created equal. There are at least 28 types in the human body, but only three matter for supplementation. <strong>Type I</strong> is the workhorse of skin, comprising 80% of dermal collagen and providing firmness and tensile strength. <strong>Type III</strong> partners with Type I in skin and blood vessels — it is abundant in infant skin and declines faster with age than Type I, which is why young skin looks "bouncy" and aged skin does not. <strong>Type II</strong> is found almost exclusively in cartilage and joint tissues and is irrelevant for skin goals, though it is the correct choice for joint-specific supplements.</p>

    <div class="vs-strip">
      <div class="vs-item"><strong>Type I</strong><p>80% of dermal collagen. Provides skin firmness, elasticity, and tensile strength. Sourced from marine (fish skin) or bovine (cow hide). The non-negotiable for any skin supplement.</p></div>
      <div class="vs-item"><strong>Type III</strong><p>Partners with Type I in skin. Abundant in younger skin, declines rapidly after age 40. Sourced from bovine. A bovine collagen naturally contains both I and III.</p></div>
      <div class="vs-item"><strong>Type II</strong><p>Found in cartilage, not skin. Skip Type II products for skin goals — they are formulated for joint support. Choose Type II only if joints are your primary target.</p></div>
    </div>

