    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Collagen Supplements for Skin</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do collagen supplements really work for skin?</summary><p>Yes — 19 RCTs with 1,125 participants have consistently shown measurable improvements in skin hydration, elasticity, and wrinkle depth at daily doses of 2.5-10g hydrolyzed collagen, typically after 8-12 weeks.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What are the 5 signs that collagen is working?</summary><p>Improved hydration (4 weeks), better elasticity (8 weeks), reduced fine lines (12 weeks), stronger nails, and thicker hair. Joint comfort often reported alongside skin changes.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Which is better for skin: collagen gummies, powder, liquid, or capsules?</summary><p>All formats work if the daily peptide dose is clinically effective. Gummies win on compliance (84% continue 90+ days), powders win on dose (10-20g) and cost. Pick the format you will take consistently for 12+ weeks.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What type of collagen is best for skin?</summary><p>Type I (80% of dermal collagen, provides firmness) partnered with Type III (skin structure support). Type II is for joints, not skin. Marine Type I has the smallest peptide size for absorption.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much collagen should I take daily for skin?</summary><p>Clinical trials use 2.5-10g daily. 5g is the most common effective dose. Take with 70-100mg vitamin C to enable collagen synthesis.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are collagen gummies as effective as collagen powder?</summary><p>Yes when they deliver 2.5g+ per serving. Powders offer higher doses (10-20g), but gummies win on real-world compliance — 84% of users continue gummies past 90 days versus 32% for powders.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>When will I see results from collagen supplements?</summary><p>Hydration at 4 weeks, elasticity at 8 weeks, wrinkle reduction at 12 weeks. Stopping causes regression within 12 weeks — collagen is a maintenance supplement.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the downside of taking collagen?</summary><p>Generally safe. Mild bloating, digestive upset, and taste issues with some marine products. Allergen concerns: fish (marine collagen), shellfish, eggs. Not suitable for strict plant-based diets.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do I need vitamin C with collagen for skin?</summary><p>Yes — vitamin C is an essential cofactor for the enzymes (prolyl and lysyl hydroxylase) that convert collagen peptides into functional skin protein. 70-100mg daily is sufficient.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take collagen every day long-term?</summary><p>Yes. 12-month clinical trials show no adverse effects. Continuous daily use is recommended — stopping causes regression of skin benefits within 12 weeks.</p></details>

